# BoostrapIcons
Bootstrap icon gallery for FileMaker
<p>The <a href="https://icons.getbootstrap.com/" target="_blank">Bootstrap Icons</a> library is an excellent resource for a huge selection of well-designed, clear, and
            professional-looking SVG icons with a consistent visual style. It's also free and open source!</p>
          <h4>The problem</h4>
            <p>Many FileMaker developers are already aware of the Bootstrap icon gallery and use it frequently to download
            SVGs and import them into their solutions; They also know that a successful import can be hit or miss.
            Once imported into FileMaker, many SVGs render very differently than they appear in the Bootstrap gallery,
            making them unrecognizable and unusable.</p>
          <p>
          <div class="card mb-3">
            <img
              src="data:image/png;base64,"
              class="card-img-top">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">Icons often look distorted or strange when imported into FileMaker</h5>
              <p class="card-text">The backpack icon on the left, for example, is how it appears in the Bootstrap gallery and the icon
                on the right is how it appears after the SVG is imported into FileMaker.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <h4>The solution</h4>
          <p>
            The challenge seems to be that Bootstrap icons use relative vector paths that don't render as expected in FileMaker. Once the <code>d</code> attribute of each <code>&lt;path&gt;</code> element of the SVG is converted to
            absolute instead of relative, the icons successfully render in FileMaker. Other SVG conversion tools for FileMaker prepare the icon for use by adding the <code>class="fm_fill"</code> attribute, for example, but don't resolve the rendering issues.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each icon in this Bootstrap Icons for FileMaker gallery has been <b>converted to use absolute paths</b>, so they
            are <b>FileMaker-ready</b>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Plus, you can search for icons by name or keyword and quickly import any icon into your FileMaker file by clicking the 'copy'
            button to copy a FileMaker snippet of a button layout object pre-loaded with the icon to your clipboard and then pasting it onto a layout in your file.
          </p>
        </div>
